# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asciidoc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] AsciiDoc is a lightweight, semantic markup language primarily designed for writing technical documentation.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] The language can be used to produce a variety of presentation-rich output formats, all from content encoded in a concise, human-readable, plain text format.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] The AsciiDoc syntax is intuitive because it builds on well-established, plain text conventions for marking up and structuring text.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] Someone unfamiliar with AsciiDoc can probably guess the purpose of many of its syntax elements just by looking at them.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] That’s because the elements of the syntax were carefully chosen to look like what they mean (a practice long employed by the tech industry).
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] An AsciiDoc processor can parse and comprehend an AsciiDoc source document and convert the parsed document structure into one or more output formats, such as HTML, PDF, EPUB3, man(ual) page, or DocBook.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] The AsciiDoc language isn’t coupled to the output produced from it.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] The ability to produce multiple output formats is one of the main advantages of AsciiDoc.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] This capability enables it to be used in static site generators, help text, book publishing, IDEs, git tools and services, CI/CD systems, and other novel uses.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] AsciiDoc bridges the gap between ease of writing and the rigorous requirements of technical authoring and publishing.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] AsciiDoc only requires a text editor to read or write, thereby offering a low bar to getting started.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] You’re reading the user-facing documentation for the AsciiDoc language as it’s implemented in Asciidoctor.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] This documentation does not cover how to set up and use Asciidoctor to process AsciiDoc content.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] You can find that documentation in the Asciidoctor section of this website.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] This documentation has been submitted as the initial contribution for the AsciiDoc Language project at Eclipse.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] That project will use this documentation as the basis for drafting a specification for the AsciiDoc language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] It will also be used as the draft of the user-facing guide for the AsciiDoc Language, which will also be maintained by that project.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] Until the first version of the AsciiDoc Language Specification is ratified, AsciiDoc is defined by the Asciidoctor implementation.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] There is no other official definition of the language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-latest] The documentation for AsciiDoc will remain on this site until the AsciiDoc Language project starts publishing its own documentation for the AsciiDoc Language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc is a plain text markup language for writing technical content.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] It’s packed with semantic elements and equipped with features to modularize and reuse content.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc content can be composed using a text editor, managed in a version control system, and published to multiple output formats.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc provides all the semantic elements you need to write and publish technical books.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] You’ll also find AsciiDoc to be an ideal fit for documentation.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] And yet, it’s simple enough to use for READMEs or taking notes.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Explore the possibilities by browsing these screenshots.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] When you write in AsciiDoc, you use plain text.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] That means the bulk of what you type are the words you want to communicate.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] You only add markup characters when you need to encode meaning that can’t otherwise be inferred.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] For example, a section title starts with a series of equals signs and an unordered list item begins with one or more asterisks.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Try writing AsciiDoc in the editor below to see for yourself!
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc is designed to strike a balance between systematic, machine-oriented syntax and natural language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] This design affords AsciiDoc the ability to capture and encode nearly all the semantics of a highly-structured language while still being readable in source form.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Want to see how AsciiDoc stacks up against alternatives?
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Browse the sample documents in this section to compare.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] DocBook is an **XML schema** for writing books and manuals about technical subjects.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] It has an extensive catalog of tags for denoting content structures and elements.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Although **well-supported by tools**, writing in DocBook is tedious because the **content is overshadowed** by the markup, there are **a lot of tags** to remember, and **XML indentation** can be a major distraction.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Markdown is a **lightweight** markup language for producing HTML.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Markdown builds on basic **plain text conventions** for formatting content.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] While approachable to a broad audience, it **stops short** of being a technical writing language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] The need for **syntax extensions** quickly enters the picture.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] In reality, Markdown is the basis for a variety of markup languages that often **deviate widely**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc appears **strikingly similar** to Markdown, making way for an easy transition.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Where AsciiDoc shines is in **its depth**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc provides all the essential elements in **technical writing** out of the box.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Its syntax can be elaborated without having to fundamentally change the language, assuring users that it’s still **standard AsciiDoc**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] DITA is an **XML schema** for representing a broad range of information.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Its architecture encourages **content modularity** and reuse, **portable references**, and **controlled extension** of its vocabulary.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] These goals are met using a **complex system** of XML tags, concepts, and toolchains.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] DITA’s complexity means it has a substantial learning curve and is **sparsely supported**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc fits the same architectural goals into an **XML-free** package and is **widely supported**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Documents can be partitioned into **units of content** and reused with the include directive.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Document references are defined **source-to-source** and translated into links between published files.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Syntax extensions invite **new markup and integrations** while keeping the language consistent.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] reStructuredText is **plain text markup** for use in docstrings and formal documentation.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] It offers an extensible syntax for producing structured output.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] It’s **line-oriented** design keeps the content clear and the separation of blocks evident.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] However, its reliance on **indentation**, non-traditional notation, and **syntax variations** make the language **esoteric** and hard for newcomers to grasp.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc aims to provide an **easy-to-read**, what-you-see-is-what-you-get syntax.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] It attains this goal by making most **indentation insignificant**, using clear block boundaries, and relying on **conventional notation**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc is composed of **a few patterns**, such as delimited blocks, macros, and formatting pairs.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] A newcomer can pick up the syntax mostly by intuition alone.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] As the most basic **building block** of the web, HTML gives structure to **web content**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] But it also assumes a lot of **presentation responsibilities**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] It’s rare to find an HTML document focused solely on content.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Its forte is in assembling **high fidelity web pages**, not as a technical writing format.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] It has all the **ceremony of XML** with only a fraction of its presentation-agnostic semantics.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Although AsciiDoc was initially conceived as a DocBook shorthand, it’s now mostly used to **generate HTML**.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] By producing the HTML, content is **not impacted by redesigns** and **content variations**, like slides or eBooks, can be created from the same source.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] AsciiDoc processors bundle a **stylesheet** that requires **no web development** to achieve a professional look.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] The AsciiDoc Language specification was launched to ensure that AsciiDoc continues to evolve and that it’s processed consistently by implementations across language runtimes, authoring environments, and application integrations.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] The specification is managed and governed by the AsciiDoc Language project and, at a higher level, by the AsciiDoc Working Group at the Eclipse Foundation.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Development of the specification is currently underway.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Write, validate, and preview your AsciiDoc content in your favorite text editor, IDE, or browser.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Convert AsciiDoc documents to HTML, DocBook, PDF, and more using an AsciiDoc processor.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc-org] Publish content using site generators or build tools that understand how to process AsciiDoc.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] The AsciiDoc format is being standardized by the Eclipse Foundation.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] AsciiDoc was created in 2002 by Stuart Rackham, who published tools (*asciidoc* and *a2x*), written in the programming language Python to convert plain text, *human readable* files to commonly used published document formats.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Implementations also exist in Ruby (named *Asciidoctor*, released in 2013), the Java ecosystem via JRuby, the JavaScript ecosystem via Opal.js, and in Haskell and Go.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Since the start of the technical standardizing process in 2019, the Asciidoctor project has aimed to produce an independent, compatible implementation of the AsciiDoc specification in the making, with the support of Stuart Rackham, the original author of the language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] The official website of the AsciiDoc language has since begun linking to Asciidoctor's documentation of the language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] The start of the standardizing process in 2019 coincided with the release of Asciidoctor 2.0 and several parts of syntax being deprecated, such as single quotation marks (`'`) to indicate italics.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Legacy syntax remains available through a compatibility mode.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] The original Python implementation by Stuart Rackham continues to be developed, and named *AsciiDoc.py*.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Since 2021, its documentation describes it as legacy, and formally targets the older rendition of the language.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Most of the Git project documentation is written in AsciiDoc.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Some of O'Reilly Media's books and e-books are authored using AsciiDoc mark-up.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Red Hat's product documentation is written in AsciiDoc.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] Asciidoctor is usable within GitHub and GitLab.
[src:asciidoc/asciidoc] The JetBrains IDE ecosystem supports AsciiDoc editing through plugins such as AsciiDoc and AsciiDoc Pro, which provide AsciiDoc documentation support including live preview, syntax highlighting and PDF export.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] On this page, you’ll learn about the overall structure of an AsciiDoc document.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Don’t worry about the details of the syntax at this point.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] That topic will be covered thoroughly later in the documentation.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Right now, we’re just aiming to get a sense of what makes up an AsciiDoc document.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] AsciiDoc is a plain text writing format with no boilerplate enclosure or prologue.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] An AsciiDoc document may consist of only a single sentence (or even a single character, to be academic).
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] The example below is a valid AsciiDoc document.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] It contains a single paragraph that consists of a single sentence.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Of course, you can have more content than a single sentence!
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] What we want to emphasize here is that it’s simple to get started.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] An AsciiDoc document is a series of blocks that are stacked linewise.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] These blocks are typically offset from one another by an empty line.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] An AsciiDoc document may begin with a document header.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Although the document header is optional, it’s often used because it allows you to specify a document title as well as document-wide configuration and reusable text in the form of document attributes.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Almost any combination of blocks constitutes a valid AsciiDoc document (with some structural requirements dictated by the document type).
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Documents can range from a single sentence to a multi-part book.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] The line is a significant building block in AsciiDoc.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] A line is defined as text that’s separated on either side by a newline character or the boundary of the document.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Many aspects of the syntax must occupy a whole line.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] That’s why we say AsciiDoc is a line-oriented language.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] For example, a section title must be on a line by itself.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] The same is true for an attribute entry, a block title, a block attribute list, a block macro, a list item, a block delimiter, and so forth.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Notice that the attribute entry must be explicitly continued to extend onto another line.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] For example, a single empty line separates the header from the body.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Many blocks are also separated by an empty line, as you saw in the example earlier with two paragraphs.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] In contrast, lines within paragraph content are insignificant.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Keep these points in mind as you’re learning about the AsciiDoc syntax.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Blocks in an AsciiDoc document lay down the document structure.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Some blocks may contain other blocks, so the document structure is inherently hierarchical (i.e., a tree structure).
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] You can inspect this section structure, for example, by enabling the automatic table of contents.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Examples of blocks include paragraphs, sections, lists, delimited blocks, tables, and block macros.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Blocks are easy to identify because they’re usually offset from other blocks by an empty line (though not always required).
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Blocks always start on a new line, terminate at the end of a line, and are aligned to the left margin.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Every block can have one or more lines of block metadata.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] This metadata can be in the form of block attributes, a block anchor, or a block title.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] These metadata lines must be above and directly adjacent to the block itself.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Sections, non-verbatim delimited blocks, and AsciiDoc table cells may contain other blocks.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Despite the fact that blocks form a hierarchy, even nested blocks start at the left margin.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] By requiring blocks to start at the left margin, it avoids the tedium of having to track and maintain levels of indentation.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] It also happens to make the content more reusable.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Surrounded by the markers, delimiters, and metadata lines is the text.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] The text is the main focus of a document and the reason the AsciiDoc syntax gives it so much room to breathe.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Text is most often found in the lines of a block (e.g., paragraph), the block title (e.g., section title), and in list items, though there are other places where it can exist.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Substitutions interpret markup as text formatting, replace macros with text or non-text elements, expand attribute references, and perform other sorts of text replacement.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Normal text is subject to all substitutions, unless specified otherwise.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Verbatim text is subject to a minimal set of substitutions to allow it to be displayed in the output as it appears in the source.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] It’s also possible to disable all substitutions in order to pass the text through to the output unmodified (i.e., raw).
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] The parsing of text ends up being a mix of inline elements and other forms of transformations.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] An AsciiDoc file is a text file that has the *.adoc* file extension (e.g., *document.adoc*).
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] Most AsciiDoc processors assume the text in the file uses UTF-8 encoding.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] UTF-16 encodings are supported only if the file starts with a BOM.
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] An AsciiDoc processor can process AsciiDoc from a string (i.e., character sequence).
[src:asciidoc/document-structure] However, most of the time you’ll save your AsciiDoc documents to a file.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] A **lightweight markup language** (**LML**), also termed a **simple** or **humane markup language**, is a markup language with simple, unobtrusive syntax.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] It is designed to be easy to write using any generic text editor and easy to read in its raw form.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] It is used in applications where it may be necessary to read the raw document and the final rendered output.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] For instance, a person downloading a software library might prefer to read the documentation in a text editor rather than a web browser.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Another use for such languages is to provide for data entry in web-based publishing, as in blogs and wikis, where the input interface is a simple text box.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] The server software then converts the input into a common document markup language like HTML.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Lightweight markup languages were originally used on text-only displays which could not display characters in italics or bold, so informal methods to convey this information had to be developed.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] This formatting choice was naturally carried forth to plain-text email communications.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Console browsers may also resort to similar display conventions.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] In 1986 international standard SGML provided facilities to define and parse lightweight markup languages using grammars and tag implication.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] The 1998 W3C XML is a profile of SGML that omits these facilities.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] However, no SGML document type definition (DTD) for any of the languages listed below is known.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Lightweight markup languages can be categorized by their tag types.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages distinguish between markup for lines or blocks and for shorter spans of texts, but some only support inline markup.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some markup languages are tailored for a specific purpose, such as documenting computer code (e.g., POD, reST, RD) or being converted to a certain output format (usually HTML or LaTeX) and nothing else, others are more general in application.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] This includes whether they are oriented on textual presentation or on data serialization.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Presentation oriented languages include AsciiDoc, atx, BBCode, Creole, Crossmark, Djot, Epytext, Haml, JsonML, MakeDoc, Markdown, Org-mode, POD (Perl), reST (Python), RD (Ruby), Setext, SiSU, SPIP, Xupl, Texy!, Textile, txt2tags, UDO and Wikitext.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Data serialization oriented languages include Curl (homoiconic, but also reads JSON; every object serializes), JSON, and YAML.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Markdown's own syntax does not support class attributes or id attributes; however, since Markdown supports the inclusion of native HTML code, these features can be implemented using direct HTML.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] txt2tags' own syntax does not support class attributes or id attributes; however, since txt2tags supports inclusion of native HTML code in tagged areas, these features can be implemented using direct HTML when saving to an HTML target.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki does not support HTML import natively, but HTML to DokuWiki converters and importers exist and are mentioned in the official documentation.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki does not support class or id attributes, but can be set up to support HTML code, which does support both features.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] HTML code support was built-in before release 2023-04-04.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] In later versions, HTML code support can be achieved through plug-ins, though it is discouraged.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Although usually documented as yielding italic and bold text, most lightweight markup processors output semantic HTML elements `em` and `strong` instead.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Monospaced text may either result in semantic `code` or presentational `tt` elements.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Few languages make a distinction, e.g., Textile, or allow the user to configure the output easily, e.g., Texy.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] LMLs sometimes differ for multi-word markup where some require the markup characters to replace the inter-word spaces (*infix*).
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some languages require one character as prefix and suffix, others need two or even three, or support both with slightly different meaning, e.g., different levels of emphasis.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Gemtext does not have any inline formatting, monospaced text (called preformatted text in the context of Gemtext) must have the opening and closing ``` on their own lines.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] In HTML, text is emphasized with the `<em>` and `<strong>` element types, whereas `<i>` and `<b>` traditionally mark up text to be italicized or bold-faced, respectively.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word and Outlook, and accordingly other word processors and mail clients that strive for a similar user experience, support the basic convention of using asterisks for boldface and underscores for italic style.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] While Word removes the characters, Outlook retains them.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] In HTML, removed or deleted and inserted text is marked up with the `<del>` and `<ins>` element types, respectively.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] However, legacy element types `<s>` or `<strike>` and `<u>` are still also available for stricken and underlined spans of text.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] AsciiDoc, ATX, Creole, MediaWiki, PmWiki, reST, Slack, Textile and WhatsApp do not support dedicated markup for underlining text.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Textile does, however, support insertion via the `+inserted+` syntax.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] ATX, Creole, MediaWiki, PmWiki, reST and Setext do not support dedicated markup for striking through text.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki supports HTML-like `<del>stricken</del>` syntax, even with embedded HTML disabled.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] AsciiDoc supports stricken text through a built-in *text span* prefix: `[.line-through]#stricken#`.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Quoted computer code is traditionally presented in typewriter-like fonts where each character occupies the same fixed width.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] HTML offers the semantic `<code>` and the deprecated, presentational `<tt>` element types for this task.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] The second style is based on repeated markers (e.g., hash `#`, equals `=` or asterisk `*`) at the start of the heading itself, where the number of repetitions indicates the (sometimes inverse) heading level.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages also support the reduplication of the markers at the end of the line, but whereas some make them mandatory, others do not even expect their numbers to match.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Org-mode supports indentation as a means of indicating the level.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] BBCode does not support section headings at all.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] POD and Textile choose the HTML convention of numbered heading levels instead.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word supports auto-formatting paragraphs as headings if they do not contain more than a handful of words, no period at the end and the user hits the enter key twice.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] For lower levels, the user may press the tabulator key the according number of times before entering the text, i.e., one through eight tabs for heading levels two through nine.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Hyperlinks can either be added inline, which may clutter the code because of long URLs, or with named `alias` or numbered `id` references to lines containing nothing but the address and related attributes and often may be located anywhere in the document.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages allow the author to specify text `Text` to be displayed instead of the plain address `http://example.com` and some also provide methods to set a different link title `Title` which may contain more information about the destination.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] LMLs that are tailored for special setups, e.g., wikis or code documentation, may automatically generate named anchors (for headings, functions etc.) inside the document, link to related pages (possibly in a different namespace) or provide a textual search for linked keywords.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages employ (double) square or angular brackets to surround links, but hardly any two languages are completely compatible.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Many can automatically recognize and parse absolute URLs inside the text without further markup.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Gemtext and setext links must be on a line by themselves, they cannot be used inline.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Org-mode's normal link syntax does a text search of the file.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] You can also put in dedicated targets with `<<id>>`.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] HTML requires an explicit element for the list, specifying its type, and one for each list item, but most lightweight markup languages need only different line prefixes for the bullet points or enumerated items.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some languages rely on indentation for nested lists, others use repeated parent list markers.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word automatically converts paragraphs that start with an asterisk `*`, hyphen-minus `-` or greater-than bracket `>` followed by a space or horizontal tabulator as bullet list items.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Languages differ on whether they support optional or mandatory digits in numbered list items, which kinds of enumerators they understand (e.g., decimal digit *1*, roman numerals *i* or *I*, alphabetic letters *a* or *A*) and whether they support to keep explicit values in the output format.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some Markdown dialects, for instance, will respect a start value other than 1, but ignore any other explicit value.
[src:asciidoc/lightweight-markup-language] Slack assists the user in entering enumerated and bullet lists, but does not actually format them as such, i.e., it just includes a leading digit followed by a period and a space or a bullet character `•` in front of a line.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] A **markup language** is a text-encoding system which specifies the structure and formatting of a document and potentially the relationships among its parts.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Markup can control the display of a document or enrich its content to facilitate automated processing.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] A markup language is a set of rules governing what markup information may be included in a document and how it is combined with the content of the document in a way to facilitate use by humans and computer programs.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The idea and terminology evolved from the marking up of paper manuscripts (e.g., with revision instructions by editors), traditionally written with a red pen or blue pencil on authors' manuscripts.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Older markup languages, which typically focus on typesetting and presentation, include troff, TeX, and LaTeX.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Scribe and most modern markup languages, such as XML, identify document components (for example headings, paragraphs, and tables), with the expectation that technology, such as stylesheets, will be used to apply formatting or other processing.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Some markup languages, such as the widely used HTML, have pre-defined presentation semantics, meaning that their specifications prescribe some aspects of how to present the structured data on particular media.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] HTML, like DocBook, Open eBook, JATS, and many others, are based on the markup metalanguages XML and SGML.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] That is, SGML and XML allow designers to specify particular schemas, which determine which elements, attributes, and other features are permitted, and where.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] A key characteristic of most markup languages is that they allow combining markup with content such as text and pictures.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] For example, if a few words in a sentence need to be emphasized, or identified as a proper name, defined term, or another special item, the markup may be inserted between the characters of the sentence.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The word *markup* is derived from the traditional publishing practice of *marking up* a manuscript, which involves adding handwritten annotations in the form of conventional symbolic printer's instructions—in the margins and text of a paper or printed manuscript.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] For centuries, this task was done primarily by skilled typographers known as *markup men* or *markers* who marked up text to indicate what typeface, style, and size should be applied to each part, and then passed the manuscript to others for typesetting by hand or machine.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The markup was also commonly applied by editors, proofreaders, publishers, and graphic designers, and by authors themselves, all of whom might also mark things such as corrections and changes.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] There are three general categories of electronic markup, articulated by James Coombs, Allen Renear, and Steven DeRose in 1987, and Tim Bray in 2003.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Presentational markup is used by traditional word-processing systems.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Binary codes embedded within document text produce the WYSIWYG ('what you see is what you get') effect.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Such markup is usually hidden from human users, even authors and editors.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Such systems use procedural and descriptive markup internally but convert them to present the user with formatted arrangements of type.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Markup is embedded in text which provides instructions for programs to process the text.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Well-known examples include troff, TeX, and Markdown.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Generally, software processes the text sequentially from beginning to end, following the instructions as encountered.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Such text is often edited with the markup visible and directly manipulated by the author.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Popular procedural markup systems usually include programming constructs, especially macros, allowing complex sets of instructions to be invoked by a simple name (and perhaps a few parameters).
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] This is much faster, less error-prone, and more maintenance-friendly than re-stating the same or similar instructions in many places.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Descriptive markup is specifically used to describe parts of the document for what they are, rather than how they should be processed.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Well-known systems that provide many such labels include LaTeX, HTML, and XML.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The objective is to decouple the structure of the document from any particular treatment or rendition of it.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Such markup is often described as *semantic*.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] An example of a descriptive markup is HTML's `<cite>` tag, which is used to label a citation.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Descriptive markup—sometimes called *logical markup* or *conceptual markup*—encourages authors to write in a way that describes the material conceptually, rather than visually.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] There is considerable overlap and concurrent use of markup types.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In modern word-processing systems, presentational markup is often saved in descriptive-markup-oriented systems such as XML, and then processed procedurally by implementations.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The programming in procedural-markup systems, such as TeX, may be used to create higher-level markup systems that are more descriptive in nature, such as LaTeX.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In recent years, several markup languages have been developed with ease of use as a key goal, and without input from standards organizations, aimed at allowing authors to create formatted text via web browsers, for example in wikis and web forums.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] These are sometimes called lightweight markup languages.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Markdown, BBCode, and the markup language used by Wikipedia are examples of such languages.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The first well-known public presentation of markup languages in computer text processing was made by William W.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Tunnicliffe at a conference in 1967, although he preferred to call it *generic coding.* It can be seen as a response to the emergence of processing programs such as RUNOFF that each used their own control notation, often specific to the target typesetting device.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In the 1970s, Tunnicliffe led the development of a standard called GenCode for the publishing industry.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Book designer Stanley Rice published speculation along similar lines in 1970.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Brian Reid, in his 1980 dissertation at Carnegie Mellon University, developed a theory and working implementation of descriptive markup in actual use.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] However, IBM researcher Charles Goldfarb is more commonly considered the inventor of markup languages.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Goldfarb developed the basic idea while working on a primitive document management system intended for law firms in 1969, and helped invent IBM's Generalized Markup Language (GML) later that same year.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] GML was first publicly disclosed in 1973.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In 1975, Goldfarb moved from Cambridge, Massachusetts to Silicon Valley and became a product planner at the IBM Almaden Research Center.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] There, he convinced IBM's executives to deploy GML commercially in 1978 as part of IBM's Document Composition Facility product, and it was widely used in business within a few years.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML), the first standard descriptive markup language, was based on both GML and GenCode.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] It was the result of an International Organization for Standardization (ISO) committee that was first chaired by Tunnicliffe, and which Goldfarb also worked on beginning in 1974.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Goldfarb eventually became chair of the committee.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] SGML was first released by ISO as the ISO 8879 standard in October 1986.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Some early examples of computer markup languages available outside the publishing industry can be found in typesetting tools on Unix systems such as troff and nroff.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In these systems, formatting commands were inserted into the document text so that typesetting software could format the text according to the editor's specifications.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] It was a trial and error iterative process to correctly print a document.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The availability of WYSIWYG publishing software supplanted much use of these languages among casual users, though professional publishing work still uses markup to specify the non-visual structure of texts, and WYSIWYG editors now usually save documents in a markup-language-based format.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Another major publishing standard is TeX, created and refined by Donald Knuth in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] TeX concentrated on the detailed layout of text and font descriptions to typeset mathematical books.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] This required Knuth to spend considerable time investigating the art of typesetting.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] TeX is mainly used in academia, where it is a *de facto* standard in many scientific disciplines.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] A TeX macro package known as LaTeX provides a descriptive markup system on top of TeX, and is widely used both among the scientific community and the publishing industry.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The first language to make a clear distinction between structure and presentation was Scribe, developed by Brian Reid and described in his doctoral thesis in 1980.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Scribe was revolutionary in a number of ways, introducing the idea of styles separated from the marked-up document, and a grammar that controlled the usage of descriptive elements.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Scribe influenced the development of GML and later SGML, and is a direct ancestor to HTML and LaTeX.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In the early 1980s, the idea that markup should focus on the structural aspects of a document and leave the visual presentation of that structure to the interpreter led to the creation of SGML.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The language was developed by a committee chaired by Goldfarb.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] It incorporated ideas from many different sources, including Tunnicliffe's project, GenCode.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Sharon Adler, Anders Berglund, and James A.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Marke were also key members of the SGML committee.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] SGML specifies a syntax for including the markup in documents, as well as one for separately describing what tags are allowed, and where (the document type definition (DTD), later known as a schema).
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] This allows authors to create and use any markup they want, selecting tags that make the most sense to them and are named in their own natural languages, while also allowing automated verification.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Thus, SGML is properly a metalanguage, and many markup languages are derived from it.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] From the late 1980s onward, most substantial new markup languages have been based on SGML, including the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) guidelines and DocBook.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] SGML was promulgated as the ISO 8879 standard in 1986.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] SGML found wide acceptance and use in fields with very large-scale documentation requirements.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] However, many found it cumbersome and difficult to learn—a side effect of its design attempting to do too much and being too flexible.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] For example, SGML made end tags (or start tags, or both) optional in certain contexts, because its developers thought markup would be done manually by overworked support staff who would appreciate saving keystrokes.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In 1989, computer scientist Tim Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system, then specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by SGMLguid, an in-house SGML-based documentation format at CERN, and very similar to the sample schema in the SGML standard.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Berners-Lee considered HTML an SGML application.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formally defined it as such with the mid-1993 publication of the first proposal for an HTML specification: "Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)" by Berners-Lee and Dan Connolly, which included an SGML DTD to define the grammar.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] These formatting commands were derived from those used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Steven DeRose argues that HTML's use of descriptive markup (and the influence of SGML in particular) was a major factor in the success of the Web, because of the flexibility and extensibility that it enabled.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] HTML became the main markup language for creating web pages and other information that can be displayed in a web browser and is likely the most used markup language in the world in the 21st century.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] XML (Extensible Markup Language) is a widely used meta markup language.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] It was developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in a committee created and chaired by Jon Bosak.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The main purpose of XML was to simplify SGML by focusing on a particular use case—documents on the Internet.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] XML remains a metalanguage like SGML, allowing users to create any tags needed (hence *extensible*) and then describing those tags and their permitted uses.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] XML adoption was hastened by the fact that every XML document can be written so that it is also an SGML document, allowing existing SGML users and software to switch to XML fairly easily.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] At the same time, XML eliminates many complex features of SGML to simplify implementation environments such as documents and publications.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] It appears to balance simplicity and flexibility, as well as support very robust schema definitions and validation tools, and was rapidly adopted for many uses.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] XML is now widely used for communicating data between applications, serializing program data, for hardware communication protocols, vector graphics, and other uses besides documents.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] From January 2000 until HTML 5 was released, all W3C recommendations for HTML were based on XML, using XHTML (Extensible HyperText Markup Language).
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The language specification requires that XHTML documents be *well-formed* XML documents.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] This allows for more rigorous and robust documents, by avoiding many syntax errors which historically led to unwanted browser behavior, while still using document components familiar to HTML users.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Another difference is that all attribute values in tags must be quoted.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Both these differences are commonly criticized as verbose but also praised because they make it far easier to detect, localize, and repair errors.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Finally, all tag and attribute names within the XHTML namespace must be lowercase to be valid.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] HTML, on the other hand, was case-insensitive.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Many XML-based applications exist, including the Resource Description Framework as RDF/XML, XForms, DocBook, SOAP, and the Web Ontology Language (OWL).
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] For a partial list of these, see list of XML markup languages.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] A common feature of many markup languages is that they intermix the text of a document with markup instructions in the same data stream or file.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] This is not necessary; it is possible to isolate markup from text content, using pointers, offsets, IDs, or other methods to coordinate the two.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Such *standoff* markup is typical for the internal representations that programs use to work with marked-up documents.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] However, *embedded* or *inline* markup is much more common elsewhere.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The codes enclosed in angle-brackets `<like this>` are markup instructions (known as *tags*), while the text between these instructions is the actual text of the document.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The codes `h1`, `p`, and `em` are examples of *semantic* markup, in that they describe the intended purpose or the meaning of the text they include.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Specifically, `h1` means the enclosed text is a *first-level heading*, `p` means a *paragraph*, and `em` means an *emphasized* word or phrase.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] A program interpreting such structural markup may apply its own rules or styles for presenting the various pieces of text, using different typefaces, boldness, font size, indentation, color, or other styles, as desired.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] For example, a tag such as `h1` might be presented in a large bold sans-serif typeface in an article, or it might be underscored in a monospaced (fixed-width font) document, or it might not change the presentation at all.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In contrast, the `i` tag in HTML 4 is an example of *presentational* markup, which is generally used to specify a characteristic of the text without specifying the reason for that appearance.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] In this case, the `i` element dictates the use of an italic typeface.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] However, in HTML 5, this element has been repurposed with a more semantic usage: to denote "a span of text in an alternate voice or mood, or otherwise offset from the normal prose in a manner indicating a different quality of text".
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] For example, it is appropriate to use the `i` element to indicate a taxonomic designation or a phrase in another language.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The change was made to ease the transition from HTML 4 to 5 as smoothly as possible so that deprecated uses of presentational elements would preserve the most likely intended meaning.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] TEI has published extensive guidelines for how to encode texts of interest in the humanities and social sciences, developed through years of international cooperative work.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] These guidelines are used for encoding historical documents, and the works of particular scholars, periods, and genres.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] While the idea of markup language originated with text documents, they are increasingly used in the presentation of other types of information, including playlists, vector graphics, web services, content syndication, and user interfaces.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] Most of these are XML applications because XML is a well-defined and extensible language.
[src:asciidoc/markup-language] The use of XML has also led to the possibility of combining multiple markup languages into a single profile, like XHTML+SMIL and XHTML+MathML+SVG.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc is a text document format for writing notes, documentation, articles, books, ebooks, slideshows, web pages, blogs and UNIX man pages.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc files can be translated to many formats including HTML, PDF, EPUB, man page.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc is highly configurable: both the AsciiDoc source file syntax and the backend output markups (which can be almost any type of SGML/XML markup) can be customized and extended by the user.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] This is an overly large document, it probably needs to be refactored into a Tutorial, Quick Reference and Formal Reference.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If you’re new to AsciiDoc read this section and the Getting Started section and take a look at the example AsciiDoc (`*.txt`) source files in the distribution `doc` directory.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc is a plain text human readable/writable document format that can be translated to DocBook or HTML using the `asciidoc(1)` command.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You can then either use `asciidoc(1)` generated HTML directly or run `asciidoc(1)` DocBook output through your favorite DocBook toolchain or use the AsciiDoc `a2x(1)` toolchain wrapper to produce PDF, EPUB, DVI, LaTeX, PostScript, man page, HTML and text formats.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The AsciiDoc format is a useful presentation format in its own right: AsciiDoc markup is simple, intuitive and as such is easily proofed and edited.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc is light weight: it consists of a single Python script and a bunch of configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Apart from `asciidoc(1)` and a Python interpreter, no other programs are required to convert AsciiDoc text files to DocBook or HTML.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Text markup conventions tend to be a matter of (often strong) personal preference: if the default syntax is not to your liking you can define your own by editing the text based `asciidoc(1)` configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You can also create configuration files to translate AsciiDoc documents to almost any SGML/XML markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] `asciidoc(1)` comes with a set of configuration files to translate AsciiDoc articles, books and man pages to HTML or DocBook backend formats.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] DocBook has emerged as the de facto standard Open Source documentation format.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] But DocBook is a complex language, the markup is difficult to read and even more difficult to write directly — I found I was spending more time typing markup tags, consulting reference manuals and fixing syntax errors, than I was writing the documentation.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See the `README` and `INSTALL` files for install prerequisites and procedures.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Packagers take a look at Packager Notes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] There are three types of AsciiDoc documents: article, book and manpage.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] All document types share the same AsciiDoc format with some minor variations.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If you are familiar with DocBook you will have noticed that AsciiDoc document types correspond to the same-named DocBook document types.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Use the `asciidoc(1)` `-d` (`--doctype`) option to specify the AsciiDoc document type — the default document type is *article*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] By convention the `.txt` file extension is used for AsciiDoc document source files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Used for short documents, articles and general documentation.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See the AsciiDoc distribution `./doc/article.txt` example.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc defines standard DocBook article frontmatter and backmatter section markup templates (appendix, abstract, bibliography, glossary, index).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Book documents will normally be used to produce DocBook output since DocBook processors can automatically generate footnotes, table of contents, list of tables, list of figures, list of examples and indexes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc defines standard DocBook book frontmatter and backmatter section markup templates (appendix, dedication, preface, bibliography, glossary, index, colophon).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `./doc/book.txt` file in the AsciiDoc distribution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `./doc/book-multi.txt` file in the AsciiDoc distribution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Used to generate roff format UNIX manual pages.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc manpage documents observe special header title and section naming conventions — see the Manpage Documents section for details.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc defines the *synopsis* section markup template to generate the DocBook `refsynopsisdiv` section.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See also the `asciidoc(1)` man page source (`./doc/asciidoc.1.txt`) from the AsciiDoc distribution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `asciidoc(1)` command translates an AsciiDoc formatted file to the backend format specified by the `-b` (`--backend`) command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] `asciidoc(1)` itself has little intrinsic knowledge of backend formats, all translation rules are contained in customizable cascading configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Backend specific attributes are listed in the Backend Attributes section.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] This backend generates plain HTML 4.01 Transitional markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] This backend generates XHTML 1.1 markup styled with CSS2.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] This backend generates HTML 5 markup, apart from the inclusion of audio and video block macros it is functionally identical to the *xhtml11* backend.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Use this backend to generate self-contained Slidy HTML slideshows for your web browser from AsciiDoc documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The Slidy backend is documented in the distribution `doc/slidy.txt` file and online.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A minor variant of the *html4* backend to support blogpost.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Backend aliases are alternative names for AsciiDoc backends.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc comes with two backend aliases: *html* (aliased to *xhtml11*) and *docbook* (aliased to *docbook45*).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You can assign (or reassign) backend aliases by setting an AsciiDoc attribute named like `backend-alias-<alias>` to an AsciiDoc backend name.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `asciidoc(1)` `--backend` option is also used to install and manage backend plugins.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc generates *article*, *book* and *refentry* DocBook documents (corresponding to the AsciiDoc *article*, *book* and *manpage* document types).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Most Linux distributions come with conversion tools (collectively called a toolchain) for converting DocBook files to presentation formats such as Postscript, HTML, PDF, EPUB, DVI, PostScript, LaTeX, roff (the native man page format), HTMLHelp, JavaHelp and text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] There are also programs that allow you to view DocBook files directly, for example Yelp (the GNOME help viewer).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] DocBook files are validated, parsed and translated various presentation file formats using a combination of applications collectively called a DocBook *tool chain*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The function of a tool chain is to read the DocBook markup (produced by AsciiDoc) and transform it to a presentation format (for example HTML, PDF, HTML Help, EPUB, DVI, PostScript, LaTeX).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A wide range of user output format requirements coupled with a choice of available tools and stylesheets results in many valid tool chain combinations.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] One of the biggest hurdles for new users is installing, configuring and using a DocBook XML toolchain.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] `a2x(1)` can help — it’s a toolchain wrapper command that will generate XHTML (chunked and unchunked), PDF, EPUB, DVI, PS, LaTeX, man page, HTML Help and text file outputs from an AsciiDoc text file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] `a2x(1)` does all the grunt work associated with generating and sequencing the toolchain commands and managing intermediate and output files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] `a2x(1)` also optionally deploys admonition and navigation icons and a CSS stylesheet.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See the `a2x(1)` man page for more details.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] In addition to `asciidoc(1)` you also need xsltproc(1), DocBook XSL Stylesheets and optionally: dblatex or FOP (to generate PDF); `w3m(1)` or `lynx(1)` (to generate text).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The following examples generate `doc/source-highlight-filter.pdf` from the AsciiDoc `doc/source-highlight-filter.txt` source file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] On the other hand, HTML output directly from AsciiDoc is much faster, is easily customized and can be used in situations where there is no suitable DocBook toolchain (for example, see the AsciiDoc website).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] There are two commonly used tools to generate PDFs from DocBook, dblatex and FOP.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Convert the HTML Help source (`.hhp` and `.html`) files to HTML Help (`.chm`) files using the Microsoft HTML Help Compiler.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Converts AsciiDoc (`.txt`) files to DocBook XML (`.xml`) files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] These are a set of XSL stylesheets containing rules for converting DocBook XML documents to HTML, XSL-FO, manpage and HTML Help files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The stylesheets are used in conjunction with an XML parser such as xsltproc(1).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] An XML parser for applying XSLT stylesheets (in our case the DocBook XSL Stylesheets) to XML documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Generates PDF, DVI, PostScript and LaTeX formats directly from DocBook source via the intermediate LaTeX typesetting language — uses DocBook XSL Stylesheets, xsltproc(1) and `latex(1)`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The Apache Formatting Objects Processor converts XSL-FO (`.fo`) files to PDF files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The XSL-FO files are generated from DocBook source files using DocBook XSL Stylesheets and xsltproc(1).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The Microsoft HTML Help Compiler (`hhc.exe`) is a command-line tool that converts HTML Help source files to a single HTML Help (`.chm`) file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] It runs on MS Windows platforms and can be downloaded from https://www.microsoft.com/.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The AsciiDoc distribution `./dblatex` directory contains `asciidoc-dblatex.xsl` (customized XSL parameter settings) and `asciidoc-dblatex.sty` (customized LaTeX settings).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] These are examples of optional dblatex output customization and are used by `a2x(1)`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You will have noticed that the distributed HTML and HTML Help documentation files (for example `./doc/asciidoc.html`) are not the plain outputs produced using the default *DocBook XSL Stylesheets* configuration.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] This is because they have been processed using customized DocBook XSL Stylesheets along with (in the case of HTML outputs) the custom `./stylesheets/docbook-xsl.css` CSS stylesheet.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You’ll find the customized DocBook XSL drivers along with additional documentation in the distribution `./docbook-xsl` directory.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The examples that follow are executed from the distribution documentation (`./doc`) directory.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] These drivers are also used by `a2x(1)`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] This file is not used directly but is included in all the following drivers.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Generate chunked XHTML (separate HTML pages for each document section) in the `./doc/chunked` directory.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Used by `a2x(1)` to generate EPUB formatted documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Generate XSL Formatting Object (`.fo`) files for subsequent PDF file generation using FOP.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Generate Microsoft HTML Help source files for the MS HTML Help Compiler in the `./doc/htmlhelp` directory.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Generate a `roff(1)` format UNIX man page from a DocBook XML *refentry* document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Convert a DocBook XML file to a single XHTML file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If you want to see how the complete documentation set is processed take a look at the A-A-P script `./doc/main.aap`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc does not have a text backend (for most purposes AsciiDoc source text is fine), however you can convert AsciiDoc text files to formatted text using the AsciiDoc `a2x(1)` toolchain wrapper utility.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The *xhtml11* and *html5* backends embed or link CSS and JavaScript files in their outputs, there is also a themes plugin framework.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The AsciiDoc *theme* attribute is used to select an alternative CSS stylesheet and to optionally include additional JavaScript code.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] For example, the command-line option `--theme foo` (or `--attribute theme=foo`) will cause `asciidoc(1)` to search configuration file locations 1 for a sub-directory called `themes/foo` containing the stylesheet `foo.css` and optionally a JavaScript file name `foo.js`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] An AsciiDoc document consists of a series of block elements starting with an optional document Header, followed by an optional Preamble, followed by zero or more document Sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Almost any combination of zero or more elements constitutes a valid AsciiDoc document: documents can range from a single sentence to a multi-part book.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Block elements consist of one or more lines of text and may contain other block elements.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The author information line contains the author’s name optionally followed by the author’s email address.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] i.e. a first name followed by optional middle and last names followed by an email address in that order.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Multi-word first, middle and last names can be entered using the underscore as a word separator.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The email address comes last and must be enclosed in angle <> brackets.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If the author line does not match the above specification then the entire author line is treated as the first name.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The optional revision information line follows the author information line.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The revision information line can also be an RCS/CVS/SVN $Id$ marker: AsciiDoc extracts the *revnumber*, *revdate*, and *author* attributes from the $Id$ revision marker and displays them in the document header.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If an $Id$ revision marker is used the header author line can be omitted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You can override or set header parameters by passing *revnumber*, *revremark*, *revdate*, *email*, *author*, *authorinitials*, *firstname* and *lastname* attributes using the `asciidoc(1)` `-a` (`--attribute`) command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Attribute entries can also be added to the header for substitution in the header template with Attribute Entry elements.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The *title* element in HTML outputs is set to the AsciiDoc document title, you can set it to a different value by including a *title* attribute entry in the document header.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If a configuration file section named *docinfo* has been loaded then it will be included in the document header.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Typically the *docinfo* section name will be prefixed with a *+* character so that it is appended to (rather than replace) other *docinfo* sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Two docinfo files are recognized: one named `docinfo` and a second named like the AsciiDoc source file with a `-docinfo` suffix.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] For example, if the source document is called `mydoc.txt` then the document information files would be `docinfo.xml` and `mydoc-docinfo.xml` (for DocBook outputs) and `docinfo.html` and `mydoc-docinfo.html` (for HTML outputs).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The docinfo attributes control which docinfo files are included in the output files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Typically *style* and *script* elements for CSS and JavaScript inclusion.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Valid *articleinfo* or *bookinfo* child elements.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] DocBook defines numerous elements for document meta-data, for example: copyrights, document history and authorship information.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See the DocBook `./doc/article-docinfo.xml` example that comes with the AsciiDoc distribution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The rendering of meta-data elements (or not) is DocBook processor dependent.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The Preamble is an optional untitled section body between the document Header and the first Section title.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] In addition to the document title (level 0), AsciiDoc supports four section levels: 1 (top) to 4 (bottom).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Section levels are delimited by section titles.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Sections are translated using configuration file section markup templates.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `level` attribute is the section level number, it is normally just the title level number (1..4).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] However, if the `leveloffset` attribute is defined it will be added to the `level` attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `leveloffset` attribute is useful for combining documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `-n` (`--section-numbers`) command-line option generates the `sectnum` (section number) attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `sectnum` attribute is used for section numbers in HTML outputs (DocBook section numbering are handled automatically by the DocBook toolchain commands).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Section markup templates specify output markup and are defined in AsciiDoc configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] When the title text matches a configuration file `[specialsections]` entry.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If neither of the above the default `sect<level>` template is used (where `<level>` is a number from 1 to 4).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] In addition to the normal section template names (*sect1*, *sect2*, *sect3*, *sect4*) AsciiDoc has the following templates for frontmatter, backmatter and other special sections: *abstract*, *preface*, *colophon*, *dedication*, *glossary*, *bibliography*, *synopsis*, *appendix*, *index*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] These special section templates generate the corresponding Docbook elements; for HTML outputs they default to the *sect1* section template.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If no explicit section ID is specified an ID will be synthesised from the section title.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The primary purpose of this feature is to ensure persistence of table of contents links (permalinks): the missing section IDs are generated dynamically by the JavaScript TOC generator **after** the page is loaded.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If you link to a dynamically generated TOC address the page will load but the browser will ignore the (as yet ungenerated) section ID.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Example: the title *Jim’s House* would generate the ID `_jim_s_house`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Section ID synthesis can be disabled by undefining the `sectids` attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc has a mechanism for mapping predefined section titles auto-magically to specific markup templates.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] For example a title *Appendix A: Code Reference* will automatically use the *appendix* section markup template.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The mappings from title to template name are specified in `[specialsections]` sections in the Asciidoc language configuration files (`lang-*.conf`).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] `<title>` is a Python regular expression and `<template>` is the name of a configuration file markup template section.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If the `<title>` matches an AsciiDoc document section title then the backend output is marked up using the `<template>` markup template (instead of the default `sect<level>` section template).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `{title}` attribute value is set to the value of the matched regular expression group named *title*, if there is no *title* group `{title}` defaults to the whole of the AsciiDoc section title.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] If `<template>` is blank then any existing entry with the same `<title>` will be deleted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] AsciiDoc has two mechanisms for specifying non-default section markup templates: you can specify the template name explicitly (using the *template* attribute) or indirectly (using *special section titles*).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Specifying a section template attribute explicitly is preferred.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Specifying special section template names explicitly does add more noise to the source document (the *template* attribute declaration), but the intention is obvious and the syntax is consistent with other AsciiDoc elements c.f. bibliographic, Q&A and glossary lists.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Special section titles have been deprecated but are retained for backward compatibility.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Inline document elements are used to format text and to perform various types of text substitution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Inline elements and inline element syntax is defined in the `asciidoc(1)` configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] These character sequences escape special characters used by the backend markup (typically `<`, `>`, and `&` characters).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See `[specialcharacters]` configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Elements that markup words and phrases; usually for character formatting.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See `[quotes]` configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Word or word phrase patterns singled out for markup without the need for further annotation.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See `[specialwords]` configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Each replacement defines a word or word phrase pattern to search for along with corresponding replacement text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See `[replacements]` configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Document attribute names enclosed in braces are replaced by the corresponding attribute value.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Inline macros are replaced by the contents of parametrized configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Each document *Section* is processed and its constituent elements translated to the output file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The configuration file `[footer]` template section is substituted and written to the output file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] When a block element is encountered `asciidoc(1)` determines the type of block by checking in the following order (first to last): (section) Titles, BlockMacros, Lists, DelimitedBlocks, Tables, AttributeEntrys, AttributeLists, BlockTitles, Paragraphs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The default paragraph definition `[paradef-default]` is last element to be checked.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Knowing the parsing order will help you devise unambiguous macro, list and block syntax rules.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The substitutions and substitution order performed on Title, Paragraph and DelimitedBlock elements is determined by configuration file parameters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Word phrases 'enclosed in single quote characters' (acute accents) or _underline characters_ are emphasized.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Word phrases *enclosed in asterisk characters* are rendered in a strong font (usually bold).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Word phrases +enclosed in plus characters+ are rendered in a monospaced font.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Word phrases `enclosed in backtick characters` (grave accents) are also rendered in a monospaced font but in this case the enclosed text is rendered literally and is not subject to further expansion (see inline literal passthrough).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Phrases enclosed with a `single grave accent to the left and a single acute accent to the right' are rendered in single quotation marks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Phrases enclosed with ``two grave accents to the left and two acute accents to the right'' are rendered in quotation marks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Placing #hashes around text# does nothing, it is a mechanism to allow inline attributes to be applied to otherwise unformatted text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] New quote types can be defined by editing `asciidoc(1)` configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] See the Configuration Files section for details.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Quoted text can be prefixed with an attribute list.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The first positional attribute (*role* attribute) is translated by AsciiDoc to an HTML *span* element *class* attribute or a DocBook *phrase* element *role* attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] DocBook XSL Stylesheets translate DocBook *phrase* elements with *role* attributes to corresponding HTML *span* elements with the same *class* attributes; CSS can then be used to style the generated HTML.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Thus CSS styling can be applied to both DocBook and AsciiDoc generated HTML outputs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You can also specify multiple class names separated by spaces.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] CSS rules for text color, text background color, text size and text decorators are included in the distributed AsciiDoc CSS files and are used in conjunction with AsciiDoc *xhtml11*, *html5* and *docbook* outputs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Where *<color>* can be any of the sixteen HTML color names.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Underline text, overline text and **bold blue and line-through**.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Quoted must be bounded by white space or commonly adjoining punctuation characters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] These are the most commonly used type of quote.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Unconstrained quotes have no boundary constraints and can be placed anywhere within inline text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Put ^carets on either^ side of the text to be superscripted, put ~tildes on either side~ of text to be subscripted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Superscripts and subscripts are implemented as unconstrained quotes and they can be escaped with a leading backslash and prefixed with with an attribute list.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A plus character preceded by at least one space character at the end of a non-blank line forces a line break.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] It generates a line break (`br`) tag for HTML outputs and a custom XML `asciidoc-br` processing instruction for DocBook outputs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `asciidoc-br` processing instruction is handled by `a2x(1)`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A line of three or more less-than (`<<<`) characters will generate a hard page break in DocBook and printed HTML outputs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] It uses the CSS `page-break-after` property for HTML outputs and a custom XML `asciidoc-pagebreak` processing instruction for DocBook outputs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `asciidoc-pagebreak` processing instruction is handled by `a2x(1)`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Hard page breaks are sometimes handy but as a general rule you should let your page processor generate page breaks for you.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A line of three or more apostrophe characters will generate a ruler line.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] It generates a ruler (`hr`) tag for HTML outputs and a custom XML `asciidoc-hr` processing instruction for DocBook outputs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The `asciidoc-hr` processing instruction is handled by `a2x(1)`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] By default tab characters input files will translated to 8 spaces.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Tab expansion is set with the *tabsize* entry in the configuration file `[miscellaneous]` section and can be overridden in included files by setting a *tabsize* attribute in the `include` macro’s attribute list.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] © copyright, ™ trademark, ® registered trademark, — em dash, … ellipsis, → right arrow, ← left arrow, ⇒ right double arrow, ⇐ left double arrow.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] You can also include arbitrary entity references in the AsciiDoc source.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] To render a replacement literally escape it with a leading back-slash.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The Configuration Files section explains how to configure your own replacements.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Words defined in `[specialwords]` configuration file sections are automatically marked up without having to be explicitly notated.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The Configuration Files section explains how to add and replace special words.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A two line title consists of a title line, starting hard against the left margin, and an underline.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] One line titles consist of a single line delimited on either side by one or more equals characters (the number of equals characters corresponds to the section level minus one).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Setting the title’s first positional attribute or *style* attribute to *float* generates a free-floating title.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A free-floating title is rendered just like a normal section title but is not formally associated with a text body and is not part of the regular section hierarchy so the normal ordering rules do not apply.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Floating titles can also be used in contexts where section titles are illegal: for example sidebar and admonition blocks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] Floating titles do not appear in a document’s table of contents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A *BlockTitle* element is a single line beginning with a period followed by the title text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A BlockTitle is applied to the immediately following Paragraph, DelimitedBlock, List, Table or BlockMacro.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] A *BlockId* is a single line block element containing a unique identifier enclosed in double square brackets.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] It is used to assign an identifier to the ensuing block element.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The preceding example identifies the ensuing paragraph so it can be referenced from other locations, for example with `<<chapter-titles,chapter titles>>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p01] The *BlockId* element has the same syntax and serves the same function to the anchor inline macro.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] By default, only substitutions that take place inside attribute list values are attribute references, this is because not all attributes are destined to be marked up and rendered as text (for example the table *cols* attribute).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] To perform normal inline text substitutions (special characters, quotes, macros, replacements) on an attribute value you need to enclose it in single quotes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] In the following quote block the second attribute value in the AttributeList is quoted to ensure the *http* macro is expanded to a hyperlink.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Paragraphs are blocks of text terminated by a blank line, the end of file, or the start of a delimited block or a list.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] There are three paragraph syntaxes: normal, indented (literal) and admonition which are rendered, by default, with the corresponding paragraph style.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Each syntax has a default style, but you can explicitly apply any paragraph style to any paragraph syntax.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] You can also apply delimited block styles to single paragraphs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The built-in paragraph styles are: *normal*, *literal*, *verse*, *quote*, *listing*, *TIP*, *NOTE*, *IMPORTANT*, *WARNING*, *CAUTION*, *abstract*, *partintro*, *comment*, *example*, *sidebar*, *source*, *music*, *latex*, *graphviz*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Normal paragraph syntax consists of one or more non-blank lines of text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The first line must start hard against the left margin (no intervening white space).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The default processing expectation is that of a normal paragraph of text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Literal paragraphs are rendered verbatim in a monospaced font without any distinguishing background or border.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] By default there is no text formatting or substitutions within Literal paragraphs apart from Special Characters and Callouts.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The *literal* style is applied implicitly to indented paragraphs i.e. where the first line of the paragraph is indented by one or more space or tab characters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The optional *attribution* and *citetitle* attributes (positional attributes 2 and 3) specify the author and source respectively.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] A good notation has subtlety and suggestiveness which at times makes it almost seem like a live teacher.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Alternatively, you can specify the paragraph admonition style explicitly using an AttributeList element.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] By default the `asciidoc(1)` HTML backends generate text captions instead of admonition icon image links.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] To generate links to icon images define the `icons` attribute, for example using the `-a icons` command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The `iconsdir` attribute sets the location of linked icon images.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] You can override the default icon image using the `icon` attribute to specify the path of the linked image.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Use the `caption` attribute to customize the admonition captions (not applicable to `docbook` backend).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] This subsection also applies to Admonition Blocks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Delimited blocks are blocks of text enveloped by leading and trailing delimiter lines (normally a series of four or more repeated characters).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The behavior of Delimited Blocks is specified by entries in configuration file `[blockdef-*]` sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] By convention filter blocks use the listing block syntax and are implemented as distinct listing block styles.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] If the *listing* style is applied to a LiteralBlock it will be rendered as a ListingBlock (this is handy if you have a listing containing a ListingBlock).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] A sidebar is a short piece of text presented outside the narrative flow of the main text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The sidebar is normally presented inside a bordered box to set it apart from the main text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The sidebar body is treated like a normal section body.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Any AsciiDoc SectionBody element (apart from SidebarBlocks) can be placed inside a sidebar.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The contents of *CommentBlocks* are not processed; they are useful for annotations and for excluding new or outdated content that you don’t want displayed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] CommentBlocks are never written to output files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] By default the block contents is subject only to *attributes* and *macros* substitutions (use an explicit *subs* attribute to apply different substitutions).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] PassthroughBlock content will often be backend specific.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] By default no substitutions are performed, the contents are rendered as mathematical formulas.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] As he spoke there was the sharp sound of horses' hoofs and grating wheels against the curb, followed by a sharp pull at the bell.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] "Yes," he continued, glancing out of the window.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] "A nice little brougham and a pair of beauties.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Example blocks are delimited by lines of equals characters and can contain any block elements apart from Titles, BlockTitles and Sidebars) inside an example block.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Qui in magna commodo, est labitur dolorum an.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] A title prefix that can be inserted with the `caption` attribute (HTML backends).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The *ExampleBlock* definition includes a set of admonition styles (*NOTE*, *TIP*, *IMPORTANT*, *WARNING*, *CAUTION*) for generating admonition blocks (admonitions containing more than a single paragraph).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Just precede the *ExampleBlock* with an attribute list specifying the admonition style name.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Bulleted list items start with a single dash or one to five asterisks followed by some white space then some text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] List item numbers are explicit or implicit.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] List items begin with a number followed by some white space then the item text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The numbers can be decimal (arabic), roman (upper or lower case) or alpha (upper or lower case).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Decimal and alpha numbers are terminated with a period, roman numbers are terminated with a closing parenthesis.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The different terminators are necessary to ensure *i*, *v* and *x* roman numbers are are distinguishable from *x*, *v* and *x* alpha numbers.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] List items begin one to five period characters, followed by some white space then the item text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] You can use the *style* attribute (also the first positional attribute) to specify an alternative numbering style.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The numbered list style can be one of the following values: *arabic*, *loweralpha*, *upperalpha*, *lowerroman*, *upperroman*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] A predefined *compact* option is available to bulleted and numbered lists — this translates to the DocBook *spacing="compact"* lists attribute which may or may not be processed by the DocBook toolchain.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] You can set the list start number using the *start* attribute (works for HTML outputs and DocBook outputs processed by DocBook XSL Stylesheets).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Labeled list items consist of one or more text labels followed by the text of the list item.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] An item label begins a line with an alphanumeric character hard against the left margin and ends with two, three or four colons or two semi-colons.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] A list item can have multiple labels, one per line.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The list item text consists of one or more lines of text starting after the last label (either on the same line or a new line) and can be followed by nested List or ListParagraph elements.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Donec eget arcu bibendum nunc consequat lobortis.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Eget arcu bibendum nunc consequat lobortis.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The *horizontal* labeled list style (also the first positional attribute) places the list text side-by-side with the label instead of under the label.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] AsciiDoc comes pre-configured with a *qanda* style labeled list for generating DocBook question and answer (Q&A) lists.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] AsciiDoc comes pre-configured with a *glossary* style labeled list for generating DocBook glossary lists.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] For working examples see the `article.txt` and `book.txt` documents in the AsciiDoc `./doc` distribution directory.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] AsciiDoc comes with a predefined *bibliography* bulleted list style generating DocBook bibliography entries.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The `[[[<reference>]]]` syntax is a bibliography entry anchor, it generates an anchor named `<reference>` and additionally displays `[<reference>]` at the anchor position.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] For example `[[[taoup]]]` generates an anchor named `taoup` that displays `[taoup]` at the anchor position.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Cite the reference from elsewhere your document using `<<taoup>>`, this displays a hyperlink (`[taoup]`) to the corresponding bibliography entry anchor.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Another list or a literal paragraph immediately following a list item is implicitly appended to the list item; to append other block elements to a list item you need to explicitly join them to the list item with a *list continuation* (a separator line containing a single plus character).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Multiple block elements can be appended to a list item using list continuations (provided they are legal list item children in the backend markup).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] List item two continued with an open block.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] This paragraph is part of the preceding list item.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] This list is nested and does not require explicit item continuation.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] This paragraph belongs to item two of the outer list.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Generates a footnote with text `<text>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Generates a footnote with a reference ID `<id>` and text `<text>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Generates a reference to the footnote with ID `<id>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The footnote text can span multiple lines.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The *xhtml11* and *html5* backends render footnotes dynamically using JavaScript; *html4* outputs do not use JavaScript and leave the footnotes inline; *docbook* footnotes are processed by the downstream DocBook toolchain.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] A footnote [An example footnote.] ; a second footnote with a reference ID [Second footnote.] ; finally a reference to the second footnote [note2] .
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The shipped AsciiDoc configuration includes the inline macros for generating DocBook index entries.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] This inline macro generates an index term (the `<secondary>` and `<tertiary>` positional attributes are optional).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Example: `indexterm:[Tigers,Big cats]` (or, using the alternative syntax `(((Tigers,Big cats)))`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Index terms that have secondary and tertiary entries also generate separate index terms for the secondary and tertiary entries.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The index terms appear in the index, not the primary text flow.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] This inline macro generates an index term that appears in both the index and the primary text flow.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The `<primary>` should not be padded to the left or right with white space characters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Callouts are a mechanism for annotating verbatim text (for example: source code, computer output and user input).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Callout markers are placed inside the annotated text while the actual annotations are presented in a callout list after the annotated text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] Callout marks are generated by the *callout* inline macro while callout lists are generated using the *callout* list definition.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The *callout* macro and *callout* list are special in that they work together.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The *callout* inline macro is not enabled by the normal *macros* substitutions option, instead it has its own *callouts* substitution option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The callout list item index inside the angle brackets.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] An identifier formatted like `CO<listnumber>-<index>` that uniquely identifies the callout mark.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] For example `CO2-4` identifies the fourth callout mark in the second set of callout marks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] The `{coids}` attribute can be used during callout list item substitution — it is a space delimited list of callout IDs that refer to the explanatory list item.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p02] You can annotate working code examples with callouts — just remember to put the callouts inside source code comments.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Macros are a mechanism for substituting parametrized text into output documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Macros have a *name*, a single *target* argument and an *attribute list*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The usual syntax is `<name>:<target>[<attrlist>]` (for inline macros) and `<name>::<target>[<attrlist>]` (for block macros).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Inline Macros occur in an inline element context.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Predefined Inline macros include *URLs*, *image* and *link* macros.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] If the `<target>` necessitates space characters use `%20`, for example `large%20image.png`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Two AsciiDoc inline macros are provided for creating hypertext links within an AsciiDoc document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] You can use either the standard macro syntax or the (preferred) alternative.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The `<id>` is a unique string that conforms to the output markup’s anchor syntax.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The optional `<xreflabel>` is the text to be displayed by captionless *xref* macros that refer to this anchor.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The optional `<xreflabel>` is only really useful when generating DocBook output.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] You may have noticed that the syntax of this inline element is the same as that of the BlockId block element, this is no coincidence since they are functionally equivalent.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Creates a hypertext link to a document anchor.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The optional `<caption>` is the link’s displayed text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Hypertext links to files on the local file system are specified using the *link* inline macro.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *link* macro generates relative URLs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The link macro `<target>` is the target file name (relative to the file system location of the referring document).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] If `<caption>` is not specified then `<target>` is displayed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] You can use the `<filename>#<id>` syntax to refer to an anchor within a target document but this usually only makes sense when targeting HTML documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Inline images are inserted into the output document using the *image* macro.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The contents of the image file `<target>` is displayed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] To display the image its file format must be supported by the target backend application.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] HTML and DocBook applications normally support PNG or JPG files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] `<target>` file name paths are relative to the location of the referring document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] A Block macro reference must be contained in a single line separated either side by a blank line or a block delimiter.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The Block Identifier macro sets the `id` attribute and has the same syntax as the anchor inline macro since it performs essentially the same function — block templates use the `id` attribute as a block element ID.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] This is equivalent to the `[id="X30"]` AttributeList element).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *image* block macro is used to display images in a block context.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The block `image` macro has the same macro attributes as it’s inline image macro counterpart.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Block images can be titled by preceding the *image* macro with a *BlockTitle*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] DocBook toolchains normally number titled block images and optionally list them in an automatically generated *List of Figures* backmatter section.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] If you define the `data-uri` attribute then images will be embedded in XHTML outputs using the data URI scheme.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Single lines starting with two forward slashes hard up against the left margin are treated as comments.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Comment lines do not appear in the output unless the *showcomments* attribute is defined.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Comment lines have been implemented as both block and inline macros so a comment line can appear as a stand-alone block or within block elements that support inline macro expansion.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] System macros are block macros that perform a predefined task and are hardwired into the `asciidoc(1)` program.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The `include` and `include1` system macros to include the contents of a named file into the source document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The `include` macro includes a file as if it were part of the parent document — tabs are expanded and system macros processed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The contents of `include1` files are not subject to tab expansion or system macro processing nor are attribute or lower priority substitutions performed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The `include1` macro’s intended use is to include verbatim embedded CSS or scripts into configuration file headers.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Lines of text in the source document can be selectively included or excluded from processing based on the existence (or not) of a document attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] `<attribute>` is an attribute name which is optional in the trailing `endif` macro.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Document text between the `ifeval` and `endif` macros is included if the Python expression inside the square brackets is true.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Take a look at the `*.conf` configuration files in the AsciiDoc distribution for examples of conditional inclusion macro usage.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *eval*, *sys* and *sys2* block macros exhibit the same behavior as their same named system attribute references.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The difference is that system macros occur in a block macro context whereas system attributes are confined to inline contexts where attribute substitution is enabled.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The `template` block macro allows the inclusion of one configuration file template section within another.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Passthrough macros are analogous to passthrough blocks and are used to pass text directly to the output.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The substitution performed on the text is determined by the macro definition but can be overridden by the `<subslist>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The usual syntax is `<name>:<subslist>[<passtext>]` (for inline macros) and `<name>::<subslist>[<passtext>]` (for block macros).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Passthroughs, by definition, take precedence over all other text substitutions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Passes text unmodified (apart from explicitly specified substitutions).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The triple-plus passthrough is functionally identical to the *pass* macro but you don’t have to escape `]` characters and you can prefix with quoted attributes in the inline version.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The double-dollar passthrough is functionally identical to the triple-plus passthrough with one exception: special characters are escaped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Text quoted with single backtick characters constitutes an *inline literal* passthrough.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The enclosed text is rendered in a monospaced font and is only subject to special character substitution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] This makes sense since monospace text is usually intended to be rendered literally and often contains characters that would otherwise have to be escaped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] If you need monospaced text containing inline substitutions use a plus character instead of a backtick.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Delete the existing macro with this `<pattern>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] `<pattern>` is a Python regular expression and `<name>` is the name of a markup template.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] If `<name>` is omitted then it is the value of the regular expression match group named *name*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The optional `[<subslist]` is a comma-separated list of substitution names enclosed in `[]` brackets, it sets the default substitutions for passthrough text, if omitted then no passthrough substitutions are performed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Contents of this group are passed unmodified to the output subject only to *subslist* substitutions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Processed as a comma-separated list of substitution names for *passtext* substitution, overrides the the macro definition *subslist*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *html5* backend *audio* and *video* block macros generate the HTML 5 *audio* and *video* elements respectively.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The AsciiDoc table syntax looks and behaves like other delimited block types and supports standard block configuration entries.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Formatting is easy to read and, just as importantly, easy to enter.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] When technical users first start creating documents, tables (complete with column spanning and table nesting) are often considered very important.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The reality is that tables are seldom used, even in technical documentation.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Try this exercise: thumb through your library of technical books, you’ll be surprised just how seldom tables are actually used, even less seldom are tables containing block elements (such as paragraphs or lists) or spanned cells.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] This is no accident, like figures, tables are outside the normal document flow — tables are for consulting not for reading.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Tables are designed for, and should normally only be used for, displaying column oriented tabular data.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Short cells can be entered horizontally, longer cells vertically.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The default behavior is to strip leading and trailing blank lines within a cell.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] These characteristics aid readability and data entry.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] AsciiDoc table data can be *psv*, *dsv* or *csv* formatted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] AsciiDoc *psv* (*Prefix Separated Values*) and *dsv* (*Delimiter Separated Values*) formats are cell oriented — the table is treated as a sequence of cells — there are no explicit row separators.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] A Python regular expression (*psv* and *dsv* formats) or a single character (*csv* format).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Defines the table border and can take the following values: *topbot* (top and bottom), *all* (all sides), *none* and *sides* (left and right sides).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Defines which ruler lines are drawn between table rows and columns.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *grid* attribute value can be any of the following values: *none*, *cols*, *rows* and *all*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Use the *align* attribute to horizontally align the table on the page (works with HTML outputs only, has no effect on DocBook outputs).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The following values are valid: *left*, *right*, and *center*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Use the *float* attribute to float the table *left* or *right* on the page (works with HTML outputs only, has no effect on DocBook outputs).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Floating only makes sense in conjunction with a table *width* attribute value of less than 100% (otherwise the table will take up all the available space).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] *float* and *align* attributes are mutually exclusive.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Use the `unfloat::[]` block macro to stop floating.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Use the *halign* attribute to horizontally align all cells in a table.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The following values are valid: *left*, *right*, and *center* (defaults to *left*).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Overridden by Column specifiers and Cell specifiers.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Use the *valign* attribute to vertically align all cells in a table.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The following values are valid: *top*, *bottom*, and *middle* (defaults to *top*).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *options* attribute can contain comma separated values, for example: *header*, *footer*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] By default header and footer rows are omitted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] See attribute options for a complete list of available table options.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *cols* attribute is a comma separated list of column specifiers.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *width* attribute is expressed as a percentage value (*"1%"*…*"99%"*).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The width specifies the table width relative to the available width.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] HTML backends use this value to set the table width attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] It’s a bit more complicated with DocBook, see the DocBook table widths sidebar.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *filter* attribute defines an external shell command that is invoked for each cell.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The built-in *asciidoc* table style is implemented using a filter.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The AsciiDoc docbook backend generates CALS tables.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] CALS tables do not support a table width attribute — table width can only be controlled by specifying absolute column widths.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Specifying absolute column widths is not media independent because different presentation media have different physical dimensions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] To get round this limitation both DocBook XSL Stylesheets and dblatex have implemented table width processing instructions for setting the table width as a percentage of the available width.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] AsciiDoc emits these processing instructions if the *width* attribute is set along with proportional column widths (the AsciiDoc docbook backend *pageunits* attribute defaults to ***).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] To generate DocBook tables with absolute column widths set the *pageunits* attribute to a CALS absolute unit such as *pt* and set the *pagewidth* attribute to match the width of the presentation media.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Column specifiers define how columns are rendered and appear in the table cols attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Cell specifiers allow individual cells in *psv* formatted tables to be spanned, multiplied, aligned and styled.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Table styles can be applied to the entire table (by setting the *style* attribute in the table’s attribute list) or on a per column basis (by specifying the style in the table’s cols attribute).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The default style: AsciiDoc inline text formatting; blank lines are treated as paragraph breaks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Like default but all text is emphasised.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Like default but all text is in a monospaced font.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Apply the same style as the table header.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Normally used to create a vertical header in the first column.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] With this style table cells can contain any of the AsciiDoc elements that are allowed inside document sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] This style runs `asciidoc(1)` as a filter to process cell contents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] No text formatting; monospaced font; all line breaks are retained (the same as the AsciiDoc LiteralBlock element).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] All line breaks are retained (just like the AsciiDoc verse paragraph style).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] AsciiDoc makes a number of attributes available to table markup templates and tags.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Column specific attributes are available when substituting the *colspec* cell data tags.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Specifies table column absolute width units.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The nominal output page width in *pageunit* units.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Used to calculate CALS tables absolute column and table widths.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Integer value calculated from *width* and *pagewidth* attributes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Table width expressed as a percentage of the available width.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Integer value calculated from *cols* column width, *width* and *pagewidth* attributes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Column width expressed as a percentage of the table width.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Horizontal cell content alignment: *left*, *right* or *center*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Vertical cell content alignment: *top*, *bottom* or *middle*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The number of the leftmost column occupied by the cell (1…).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The number of the rightmost column occupied by the cell (1…).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Number of rows the cell should span (1…).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Number of additional rows the cell should span (0…).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] An alternative *psv* separator character *!* can be used (instead of *|*) in nested tables.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] This allows a single level of table nesting.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Columns containing nested tables must use the *asciidoc* style.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] An example can be found in `./examples/website/newtables.txt`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Fully implementing tables is not trivial, some DocBook toolchains do better than others.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] AsciiDoc HTML table outputs are rendered correctly in all the popular browsers — if your DocBook generated tables don’t look right compare them with the output generated by the AsciiDoc *xhtml11* backend or try a different DocBook toolchain.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Sooner or later, if you program in a UNIX environment, you’re going to have to write a man page.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] By observing a couple of additional conventions (detailed below) you can write AsciiDoc files that will generate HTML and PDF man pages plus the native manpage roff format.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The easiest way to generate roff manpages from AsciiDoc source is to use the `a2x(1)` command.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The `ps2pdf(1)` command is included in the Ghostscript distribution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] To find out more about man pages view the `man(7)` manpage (`man 7 man` and `man man-pages` commands).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The title line contains the man page name followed immediately by the manual section number in brackets, for example *ASCIIDOC(1)*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The title name should not contain white space and the manual section number is a single digit optionally followed by a single character.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The first manpage section is mandatory, must be titled *NAME* and must contain a single paragraph (usually a single line) consisting of a list of one or more comma separated command name(s) separated from the command purpose by a dash character.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The dash must have at least one white space character on either side.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The second manpage section is mandatory and must be titled *SYNOPSIS*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] In addition to the automatically created man page intrinsic attributes you can assign DocBook refmiscinfo element *source*, *version* and *manual* values using AsciiDoc `{mansource}`, `{manversion}` and `{manmanual}` attributes respectively.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] The *asciimath* and *latexmath* passthrough blocks along with the *asciimath* and *latexmath* passthrough macros provide a (backend dependent) mechanism for rendering mathematical formulas.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] LaTeX math can be included in documents that are processed by dblatex(1).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] For more examples see the AsciiDoc website or the distributed `doc/latexmath.txt` file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] MathJax allows LaTeX Math style formulas to be included in XHTML documents generated via the AsciiDoc *xhtml11* and *html5* backends.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] This route overcomes several restrictions of the MathML-based approaches, notably, restricted support of MathML by many mainstream browsers.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] To enable *MathJax* support you must define the *mathjax* attribute, for example using the `-a mathjax` command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] Equations are specified as explained above using the *latexmath* passthrough blocks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] By default, rendering of equations with *MathJax* requires a working internet connection and will thus not work if you are offline (but it can be configured differently).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] For more examples see the AsciiDoc website or the distributed `doc/latexmathml.txt` file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] ASCIIMath formulas can be included in XHTML documents generated using the *xhtml11* and *html5* backends.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] To enable ASCIIMath support you must define the *asciimath* attribute, for example using the `-a asciimath` command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] For more examples see the AsciiDoc website or the distributed `doc/asciimath.txt` file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] MathML is a low level XML markup for mathematics.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p03] AsciiDoc has no macros for MathML but users familiar with this markup could use passthrough macros and passthrough blocks to include MathML in output documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] AsciiDoc source file syntax and output file markup is largely controlled by a set of cascading, text based, configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] At runtime The AsciiDoc default configuration files are combined with optional user and document specific configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Configuration files contain named sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Each section begins with a section name in square brackets [].
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The section body consists of the lines of text between adjacent section headings.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Configuration options that don’t belong anywhere else.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Special characters reserved by the backend markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Definitions for quoted inline character formatting.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Lists of words and phrases singled out for special markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Find and replace substitution definitions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Used to single out special section names for specific markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Heading, section and block title definitions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Each line of text in these sections is a *section entry*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The entry value is set to a zero length string.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The entry is undefined (deleted from the configuration).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This syntax only applies to *attributes* and *miscellaneous* sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Output file line termination characters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Can include any valid Python string escape sequences.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The default value is `\r\n` (carriage return, line feed).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Should not be quoted or contain explicit spaces (use `\x20` instead).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The default extension for the output file, for example `outfilesuffix=.html`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The number of spaces to expand tab characters, for example `tabsize=4`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A *tabsize* of zero suppresses tab expansion (useful when piping included files through block filters).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Included files can override this option using the *tabsize* attribute.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] These global table related options are documented in the Table Configuration File Definitions sub-section.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The entry value is a Python regular expression containing the named group *title*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A comma separated list of document and section title underline character pairs starting with the section level 0 and ending with section level 4 underline.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A comma separated list of substitutions that are performed on the document header and section titles.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `[tags]` section contains backend tag definitions (one per line).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Tags are used to translate AsciiDoc elements to backend markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] An AsciiDoc tag definition is formatted like `<tagname>=<starttag>|<endtag>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] In this example `asciidoc(1)` replaces the | character with the emphasized text from the AsciiDoc input file and writes the result to the output file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Use the `{brvbar}` attribute reference if you need to include a | pipe character inside tag text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The optional `[attributes]` section contains predefined attributes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If the attribute value requires leading or trailing spaces then the text text should be enclosed in quotation mark (") characters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `[specialcharacters]` section specifies how to escape characters reserved by the backend markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Special characters are normally confined to those that resolve markup ambiguity (in the case of HTML and XML markups the ampersand, less than and greater than characters).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The following example causes all occurrences of the `<` character to be replaced by `&lt;`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Quoting is used primarily for text formatting.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `[quotes]` section defines AsciiDoc quoting characters and their corresponding backend markup tags.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Each section entry value is the name of a of a `[tags]` section entry.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The entry name is the character (or characters) that quote the text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `[specialwords]` section is used to single out words and phrases that you want to consistently format in some way throughout your document without having to repeatedly specify the markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The name of each entry corresponds to a markup template section and the entry value consists of a list of words and phrases to be marked up.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The examples specifies that any occurrence of `NOTE` or `IMPORTANT` should appear in a bold font.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Words and word phrases are treated as Python regular expressions: for example, the word `^NOTE` would only match `NOTE` if appeared at the start of a line.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] AsciiDoc comes with three built-in Special Word types: *emphasizedwords*, *monospacedwords* and *strongwords*, each has a corresponding (backend specific) markup template section.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Edit the configuration files to customize existing Special Words and to add new ones.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The find text can be a Python regular expression; the replace text can contain Python regular expression group references.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The only difference between the three replacement types is how they are applied.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] By default *replacements* and *replacements2* are applied in normal substitution contexts whereas *replacements3* needs to be configured explicitly and should only be used in backend configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Markup template sections supply backend markup for translating AsciiDoc elements.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Since the text is normally backend dependent you’ll find these sections in the backend specific configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Template sections differ from other sections in that they contain a single block of text instead of per line *name=value* entries.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The document content placeholder is a single | character and is replaced by text from the source element.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Use the `{brvbar}` attribute reference if you need a literal | character in the template.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This allows both a system wide copy and multiple local copies of AsciiDoc to coexist on the same host PC.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The user’s `$HOME/.asciidoc` directory (if it exists).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The directory containing the AsciiDoc source file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Explicit configuration files specified using: The `conf-files` attribute (one or more file names separated by a `|` character).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] These files are loaded in the order they are specified and prior to files specified using the `--conf-file` command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `asciidoc(1)` `--conf-file`) command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `--conf-file` option can be specified multiple times, in which case configuration files will be processed in the same order they appear on the command-line.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Backend plugin configuration files are loaded from subdirectories named like `backends/<backend>` in locations 1, 2 and 3.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Filter configuration files are loaded from subdirectories named like `filters/<filter>` in locations 1, 2 and 3.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A document attribute is comprised of a *name* and a textual *value* and is used for textual substitution in AsciiDoc documents and configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] An attribute reference (an attribute name enclosed in braces) is replaced by the corresponding attribute value.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Attribute names are case insensitive and can only contain alphanumeric, dash and underscore characters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Within each of these divisions the last processed entry takes precedence.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `AttributeEntry` block element allows document attributes to be assigned within an AsciiDoc document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Attribute entries are added to the global document attributes dictionary.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This will set an attribute reference `{authorinitials}` to the value *JB* in the current document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Where `<section_name>` is the configuration section name, `<entry_name>` is the name of the entry and `<entry_value>` is the optional entry value.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] URLs and file names in AsciiDoc macros are often quite long — they break paragraph flow and readability suffers.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The problem is compounded by redundancy if the same name is used repeatedly.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The list consists of zero or more positional attribute values followed by zero or more named attribute values.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Macros calls are suffixed with an attribute list.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The list may be empty but it cannot be omitted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] List entries are used to pass attribute values to macro markup templates.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] An attribute reference is an attribute name (possibly followed by an additional parameters) enclosed in curly braces.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] When an attribute reference is encountered it is evaluated and replaced by its corresponding text value.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If the attribute is undefined the line containing the attribute is dropped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] There are three types of attribute reference: *Simple*, *Conditional* and *System*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Simple attribute references take the form `{<name>}`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If the attribute name is defined its text value is substituted otherwise the line containing the reference is dropped from the output.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Additional parameters are used in conjunction with attribute names to calculate a substitution value.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] `<value>` is substituted if the attribute `<names>` is undefined otherwise its value is substituted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] `<value>` can contain simple attribute references.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] `<value>` is substituted if the attribute `<names>` is defined otherwise an empty string is substituted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] `<value>` is substituted if the attribute `<names>` is undefined otherwise an empty string is substituted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] `<value>` is substituted if the attribute `<names>` is defined otherwise the undefined attribute entry causes the containing line to be dropped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] `<value>` is substituted if the attribute `<names>` is not defined otherwise the containing line is dropped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] `<value1>` is substituted if the value of attribute `<names>` matches the regular expression `<regexp>` otherwise `<value2>` is substituted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If attribute `<names>` is not defined the containing line is dropped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If `<value2>` is omitted an empty string is assumed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The values and the regular expression can contain simple attribute references.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] To embed colons in the values or the regular expression escape them with backslashes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Substitutes `<value>` if `<names>` matches `<regexp>` otherwise the result is undefined and the containing line is dropped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Substitutes `<value>` if `<names>` does not match `<regexp>` otherwise the result is undefined and the containing line is dropped.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Conditional attributes with single attribute names are evaluated first so they can be used inside the multi-attribute conditional `<value>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Conditional attributes are mainly used in AsciiDoc configuration files — see the distribution `.conf` files for examples.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] System attribute references generate the attribute text value by executing a predefined action that is parametrized by one or more arguments.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Increments the document attribute (if the attribute is undefined it is set to `1`).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Same as `counter` except the it always returns a blank string.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Substitutes the result of the Python `<expression>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Passthrough version of `{eval:<expression>}` — the generated output is written directly to the output without any further substitutions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Substitutes contents of the file named `<filename>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Normally only used in configuration file markup templates (use AttributeEntries in AsciiDoc documents).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Same as `set` except that the attribute scope is local to the template.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Substitutes the stdout generated by the execution of the shell `<command>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Substitutes the stdout and stderr generated by the execution of the shell `<command>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Passthrough version of `{sys:<command>}` — the generated output is written directly to the output without any further substitutions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Substitutes the contents of the configuration file section named `<template>`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Attribute references contained in the template are substituted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Intrinsic attributes are simple attributes that are created automatically from: AsciiDoc document header parameters; `asciidoc(1)` command-line arguments; attributes defined in the default configuration files; the execution context.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The syntax and behavior of Paragraph, DelimitedBlock, List and Table block elements is determined by block definitions contained in AsciiDoc configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Each definition consists of a section title followed by one or more section entries.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Each entry defines a block parameter controlling some aspect of the block’s behavior.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Configuration file block definition sections are processed incrementally after each configuration file is loaded.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Block definition section entries are merged into the block definition, this allows block parameters to be overridden and extended by later loading configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A Python regular expression that matches the first line of a block element — in the case of DelimitedBlocks and Tables it also matches the last line.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The name of the configuration file markup template section that will envelope the block contents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The pipe (*|*) character is substituted for the block contents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] List elements use a set of (list specific) tag parameters instead of a single template.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The template name can contain attribute references allowing dynamic template selection a the time of template substitution.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A comma delimited list of element specific option names.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] In addition to being used internally, options are available during markup tag and template substitution as attributes with an empty string value named like `<option>-option` (where `<option>` is the option name).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] See attribute options for a complete list of available options.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This optional entry specifies an executable shell command for processing block content (Paragraphs, DelimitedBlocks and Tables).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The filter command can contain attribute references.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Optional comma separated list of positional attribute names.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This list maps positional attributes (in the block’s attribute list) to named block attributes.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This optional parameter specifies the default style name.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Optional style definition (see Styles below).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The following block parameters behave like document attributes and can be set in block attribute lists and style definitions: *template*, *options*, *subs*, *presubs*, *postsubs*, *filter*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A style is a set of block parameter bundled as a single named parameter.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If a block’s attribute list contains a *style* attribute then the corresponding style parameters are be merged into the default block definition parameters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Paragraph translation is controlled by `[paradef-*]` configuration file section entries.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Users can define new types of paragraphs and modify the behavior of existing types by editing AsciiDoc configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Irrespective of its position in the configuration files default paragraph document matches are attempted only after trying all other paragraph types.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This regular expression must contain the named group *text* which matches the text on the first line.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Paragraphs are terminated by a blank line, the end of file, or the start of a DelimitedBlock.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The *listelement* option specifies that paragraphs of this type will automatically be considered part of immediately preceding list items.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The *skip* option causes the paragraph to be treated as a comment (see CommentBlocks).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Optional *presubs* inline substitutions are performed on the paragraph text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If a filter command is specified it is executed and the paragraph text piped to its standard input; the filter output replaces the paragraph text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Optional *postsubs* inline substitutions are performed on the paragraph text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The paragraph text is enveloped by the paragraph’s markup template and written to the output file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The block contents are processed as a SectionBody.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The block is treated as a comment (see CommentBlocks).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Preceding attribute lists and block titles are not consumed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If a filter is specified it is executed and the block’s contents piped to its standard input.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The filter output replaces the block contents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Optional *postsubs* substitutions are performed on the block contents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The block contents is enveloped by the block’s markup template and written to the output file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] List behavior and syntax is determined by `[listdef-*]` configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The user can change existing list behavior and add new list types by editing configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This is either *bulleted*,*numbered*,*labeled* or *callout*.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] A Python regular expression that matches the first line of a list element entry.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This expression can contain the named groups *text* (bulleted groups), *index* and *text* (numbered lists), *label* and *text* (labeled lists).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The `<name>` of the `[listtags-<name>]` configuration file section containing list markup tag definitions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The tag entries (*list*, *entry*, *label*, *term*, *text*) map the AsciiDoc list structure to backend markup; see the *listtags* sections in the AsciiDoc distributed backend `.conf` configuration files for examples.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Table behavior and syntax is determined by `[tabledef-*]` and `[tabletags-*]` configuration file sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The user can change existing table behavior and add new table types by editing configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Table header, footer and body row tag definitions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] *headrow* and *footrow* table definition entries default to *bodyrow* if they are undefined.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] Table header, footer and body data tag definitions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] *headdata* and *footdata* table definition entries default to *bodydata* if they are undefined.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] If the *paragraph* tag is specified then blank lines in the cell data are treated as paragraph delimiters and marked up using this tag.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] This integer value is the printable width of the output media.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p04] The units of width in output markup width attribute values.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] AsciiDoc filters allow external commands to process AsciiDoc *Paragraphs*, *DelimitedBlocks* and *Table* content.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Filters are primarily an extension mechanism for generating specialized outputs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Filters are implemented using external commands which are specified in configuration file definitions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] There’s nothing special about the filters, they’re just standard UNIX filters: they read text from the standard input, process it, and write to the standard output.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `asciidoc(1)` command `--filter` option can be used to install and remove filters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The same option is used to unconditionally load a filter.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Attribute substitution is performed on the filter command prior to execution — attributes can be used to pass parameters from the AsciiDoc source document to the filter.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Standard practice is to install each filter in it’s own sub-directory with the same name as the filter’s style definition.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] For example the music filter’s style name is *music* so it’s configuration and filter files are stored in the `filters/music` directory.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Filters are normally accompanied by a configuration file containing a Paragraph or DelimitedBlock definition along with corresponding markup templates.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] While it is possible to create new *Paragraph* or *DelimitedBlock* definitions the preferred way to implement a filter is to add a style to the existing Paragraph and ListingBlock definitions (all filters shipped with AsciiDoc use this technique).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The filter is applied to the paragraph or delimited block by preceding it with an attribute list: the first positional attribute is the style name, remaining attributes are normally filter specific parameters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] `asciidoc(1)` auto-loads all `.conf` files found in the filter search paths unless the container directory also contains a file named `__noautoload__` (see previous section).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `__noautoload__` feature is used for filters that will be loaded manually using the `--filter` option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] AsciiDoc comes with a toy filter for highlighting source code keywords and comments.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] See also the `./filters/code/code-filter-readme.txt` file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The AsciiDoc distribution includes *source*, *music*, *latex* and *graphviz* filters, details are on the AsciiDoc website.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Filter plugins are a mechanism for distributing AsciiDoc filters.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] A filter plugin is a Zip file containing the files that constitute a filter.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `asciidoc(1)` `--filter` option is used to load and manage filer plugins.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The AsciiDoc plugin architecture is an extension mechanism that allows additional backends, filters and themes to be added to AsciiDoc.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Plugin commands and conventions are documented in the `asciidoc(1)` man page.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] You can find lists of plugins on the AsciiDoc website.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `asciidoc(1)` command has a `--help` option which prints help topics to stdout.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] To print a help topic specify the topic name as a command argument.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Help topic names can be shortened so long as they are not ambiguous.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] To change, delete or add your own help topics edit a help configuration file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The help file name `help-<lang>.conf` is based on the setting of the `lang` attribute, it defaults to `help.conf` (English).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The help file location will depend on whether you want the topics to apply to all users or just the current user.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The help topic files have the same named section format as other configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `help.conf` files are stored in the same locations and loaded in the same order as other configuration files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] When the `--help` command-line option is specified AsciiDoc loads the appropriate help files and then prints the contents of the section whose name matches the help topic name.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] If a topic name is not specified `default` is used.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] You don’t need to specify the whole help topic name on the command-line, just enough letters to ensure it’s not ambiguous.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] If a matching help file section is not found a list of available topics is printed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Writing AsciiDoc documents will be a whole lot more pleasant if you know your favorite text editor.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Learn how to indent and reformat text blocks, paragraphs, lists and sentences.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Use the vim `:gq` command to reformat paragraphs.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Execute `:help gq` command to read about the vim gq command.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `gq` command can also be used to format bulleted, numbered and callout lists.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] First you need to set the `comments`, `formatoptions` and `formatlistpat` (see the Example `~/.vimrc` file).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Indent whole paragraphs by indenting the fist line with the desired indent and then executing the `gq}` command.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] AsciiDoc diagnostic features are detailed in the Diagnostics appendix.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] If you get an error message like `'UTF-8' codec can't decode ...` then you source file contains invalid UTF-8 characters — set the AsciiDoc encoding attribute for the correct character set (typically ISO-8859-1 (Latin-1) for European languages).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] AsciiDoc attempts to validate the input AsciiDoc source but makes no attempt to validate the output markup, it leaves that to external tools such as `xmllint(1)` (integrated into `a2x(1)`).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Backend validation cannot be hardcoded into AsciiDoc because backends are dynamically configured.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] You can suppress markup expansion by placing a backslash character immediately in front of the element.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Overlapping text formatting will generate illegal overlapping markup tags which will result in downstream XML parsing errors.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] A DelimitedBlock can immediately follow a paragraph without an intervening blank line, but be careful, a single line paragraph underline may be misinterpreted as a section title underline resulting in a “closing block delimiter expected” error.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Lines beginning with numbers at the end of sentences will be interpreted as ordered list items.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The *list item out of sequence* warning makes it unlikely that this problem will go unnoticed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Special character substitution precedes attribute substitution so if attribute values contain special characters you may, depending on the substitution context, need to escape the special characters yourself.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] If any named attribute entries are present then all string attribute values must be quoted.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] You have a number of stand-alone AsciiDoc documents that you want to process as a single document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Simply processing them with a series of `include` macros won’t work because the documents contain (level 0) document titles.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The solution is to create a top level wrapper document and use the `leveloffset` attribute to push them all down one level.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The document titles in the included documents will now be processed as level 1 section titles, level 1 sections as level 2 sections and so on.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] You also want to process the section files as separate documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] This is easy because `asciidoc(1)` will quite happily process `section1.txt`, `section2.txt` and `section3.txt` separately — the resulting output documents contain the section but have no document title.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Use the `-s` (`--no-header-footer`) command-line option to suppress header and footer output, this is useful if the processed output is to be included in another file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] `asciidoc(1)` can be used as a filter, so you can pipe chunks of text through it.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] See the `[footer]` section in the AsciiDoc distribution `xhtml11.conf` configuration file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Use HTML Tidy program to tidy `asciidoc(1)` output.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The conditional inclusion of DocBook SGML markup at the end of the distribution `docbook45.conf` file illustrates how to support minor DTD variations.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The included sections override corresponding entries from preceding sections.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] If you’ve ever tried to send someone an HTML document that includes stylesheets and images you’ll know that it’s not as straight-forward as exchanging a single file.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] AsciiDoc has options to create stand-alone documents containing embedded images, stylesheets and scripts.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Reproducing presentation documents from someone else’s source has one major problem: unless your configuration files are the same as the creator’s you won’t get the same output.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The solution is to create a single backend specific configuration file using the `asciidoc(1)` `-c` (`--dump-conf`) command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] You then ship this file along with the AsciiDoc source document plus the `asciidoc.py` script.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The only end user requirement is that they have Python installed (and that they consider you a trusted source).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Ship `mydoc.txt`, `mydoc-html.conf`, and `asciidoc.py`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `-e` (`--no-conf`) option excludes the use of implicit configuration files, ensuring that only entries from the `mydoc-html.conf` configuration are used.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Adjust your style sheets to add the correct separation between block elements.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Inserting blank paragraphs containing a single non-breaking space character `{nbsp}` works but is an ad hoc solution compared to using style sheets.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] You can close off section tags up to level `N` by calling the `eval::[Section.setlevel(N)]` system macro.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] This is useful if you want to include a section composed of raw markup.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Use `xmllint(1)` to check the AsciiDoc generated markup is both well formed and valid.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `--valid` option checks the file is valid against the document type’s DTD, if the DTD is not installed in your system’s catalog then it will be fetched from its Internet location.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] If you omit the `--valid` option the document will only be checked that it is well formed.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The online W3C Markup Validation Service is the defacto standard when it comes to validating HTML (it validates all HTML standards including HTML5).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] An AsciiDoc block element is a document entity composed of one or more whole lines of text.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] AsciiDoc inline elements occur within block element textual content, they perform formatting and substitution tasks.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] An AsciiDoc block element that has a BlockTitle.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Formal elements are normally listed in front or back matter, for example lists of tables, examples and figures.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The word verbatim indicates that white space and line breaks in the source document are to be preserved in the output document.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The rationale for the changes can be found in the AsciiDoc `CHANGELOG`.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Read the `README` and `INSTALL` files (in the distribution root directory) for install prerequisites and procedures.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The distribution `Makefile.in` (used by `configure` to generate the `Makefile`) is the canonical installation procedure.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] AsciiDoc *safe mode* skips potentially dangerous scripted sections in AsciiDoc source files by inhibiting the execution of arbitrary code or the inclusion of arbitrary files.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The safe mode is disabled by default, it can be enabled with the `asciidoc(1)` `--safe` command-line option.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] Syntax highlighting is incredibly useful, in addition to making reading AsciiDoc documents much easier syntax highlighting also helps you catch AsciiDoc syntax errors as you write your documents.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] If you use the Vim editor, it comes with an AsciiDoc syntax highlighter pre-included.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] By default, it will activate for files that use the .asciidoc or .adoc file extensions.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The `asciidoc(1)` `--verbose` command-line option prints additional information to stderr: files processed, filters processed, warnings, system attribute evaluation.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] A special attribute named *trace* enables the output of element-by-element diagnostic messages detailing output markup generation to stderr.
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] The *trace* attribute can be set on the command-line or from within the document using Attribute Entries (the latter allows tracing to be confined to specific portions of the document).
[src:asciidoc/userguide-p05] This table contains a list of optional attributes that influence the generated outputs.
